# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ark-of-bulrushes
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] The flowering staff of Aaron in the biblical narrative may be an etiology of the asherah cultic object.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] Aaron’s rod, originally associated with priestly and magical powers, may have been later transferred to Moses in various biblical accounts, demonstrating his authority and divine empowerment.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] In Israelite culture, the rod (Hebrew: מַטֶּה *maṭṭeh*) was a natural symbol of authority, as the tool used by the shepherd to correct and guide his flock.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] Moses, in fact, initially carried his rod while tending his sheep, and later it became his symbol of authority over the Israelites.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] The rods of both Moses and Aaron were endowed with miraculous power during the Plagues of Egypt.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] God commanded Moses to raise his rod over the Red Sea when it was to be split and in prayer over Israel in battle; at Meribah Moses brought forth water from a stone using his rod.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] Aaron's rod – perhaps a different rod – reappears in Numbers 16–17.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] Here Korah's rebellion against Moses's proclamation of the tribe of Levi as the priesthood has been quashed and the entire congregation's ensuing rebellion has resulted in a plague, ended only by the intercession of Moses and Aaron.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] In order to "stop the complaints" of the Israelites, God commands that each of the Twelve Tribes provide a rod; and only that of the tribe chosen to become priests will miraculously sprout overnight.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] Aaron provides his rod to represent the tribe of Levi, and "it put forth buds, produced blossoms, and bore ripe almonds", as an evidence of the exclusive right to the priesthood of the tribe of Levi.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] In commemoration of this decision, it was commanded that the rod be stored "before the testimony".
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] Aaron's rod is cited as exhibiting miraculous power on its own, when not physically held by its owner.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] In Exodus 7:10–1, Aaron "cast down his rod" and it became a serpent.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] When he does so, the Pharaoh's sorcerers counter by similarly casting down their own rods, which also become serpents, but Aaron's rod swallowed them all.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] Similarly, in Numbers 17:23 it sprouted blossoms when not being held.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] Rabbinic midrash described attributes of Aaron's rod beyond those in the Biblical text.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] It is reported that the rod was made of sapphire, weighed forty seahs (a seah = 10.70 pounds), and bore the inscription דצ״ך עד״ש באח״ב (the initials of the Hebrew names of the Ten Plagues).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] God created it in the twilight of the sixth day of Creation, and delivered it to Adam when the latter was driven from paradise.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] After it had passed through the hands of Shem, Enoch, Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob successively, it came into the possession of Joseph.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] On Joseph's death the Egyptian nobles stole some of his belongings, and, among them, Jethro appropriated the staff.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] Jethro planted the staff in his garden, when its marvelous virtue was revealed by the fact that nobody could withdraw it from the ground (compare "the sword in the stone"); even to touch it was fraught with danger to life.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] This was because the Ineffable Name of God was engraved upon it.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] When Moses entered Jethro's household he read the Name, and by means of it was able to draw up the rod, for which service Zipporah, Jethro's daughter, was given to him in marriage.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] Her father had sworn that she should become the wife of the man who should be able to master the miraculous rod and of no other.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] Aaron's rod, together with its blossoms and fruit, was preserved in the Ark.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] King Josiah, who foresaw the impending national catastrophe, concealed the Ark and the objects stored with it (Aaron's rod, a vial of manna, and the holy anointing oil).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] Their whereabouts will remain unknown until, in the Messianic age, the prophet Elijah shall reveal them.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] The length of the rod can be determined by the size of the ark of the covenant as stated in Exodus 37:1 or a length of 2.5 cubits, a depth of 1.5 cubits, and a height of 1.5 cubits.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] The cubit was not defined in either SI or Imperial units.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] However, the average of the two lengths given by Rav Avraham Chaim Naeh or Chazon Ish would put a cubit at roughly 1.7 feet, putting the maximum length of the staff at 6.1' (6'1.2" or 1.9m).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] (Correction to the immediately above paragraph: The two hypotenuses referenced are not at right angles to each other, hence the Pythagorean formula does not apply to the third side.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] As discussed, the Bible ascribes similar miraculous powers to rods of Aaron and Moses.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] According to one midrash, Moses split a tree trunk into twelve portions, and gave one portion to each tribe.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] When the Rod of Aaron produced blossoms, the Israelites could not but acknowledge the significance of the token.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] This opinion seemingly assumes that the rod in Korach's rebellion was separate from the rod used for the plagues.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] Hebrews 9:4 states that Aaron's rod was kept in the Ark of the Covenant.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] The account of the blossoming of Aaron's rod contained in Clement's first letter to the Corinthians (ep.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] 43) is in haggadic-midrashic style, and may probably be ascribed to Jewish or, more strictly speaking, Jewish-Hellenistic sources.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] According to that account, Moses placed upon each of the twelve staffs the corresponding seal of the head of a tribe.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] The doors of the sanctuary were similarly sealed, to prevent anyone from having access to the rods at night.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] The miraculous flowering of the rod was also considered a type of the Incarnation of Christ and his Virgin Birth, and appears in scenes of the Annunciation to Mary.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] Accounts of Aaron's rod appear in Islamic literature.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] 1035, AH 427) Stories of the Prophets depicts Harun (Aaron) leaning on his rod, while his brother Musa's (Moses) staff miraculously turned into a snake-dragon to defeat Pharaoh's magicians.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] Lawrence entitled a novel *Aaron's Rod* in 1922.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] This book describes a flautist, Aaron Sissons, and his experiences as he journeys through a Europe exhausted by the First World War.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron-s-rod] The biblical eponymous reference, with the flute representing a magic rod, is intended to be ironic.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] According to the Old Testament of the Bible, **Aaron** (/ˈɛərən/ ⓘ *AIR-ən* or /ˈærən/ ⓘ *ARR-ən*) was an Israelite prophet, high priest, and the elder brother of Moses.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Information about Aaron comes exclusively from religious texts, such as the Hebrew Bible, the New Testament (Luke, Acts, and Hebrews), and the Quran.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The Hebrew Bible relates that, unlike Moses, who grew up in the Egyptian royal court, Aaron and his elder sister Miriam remained with their kinsmen in the northeastern region of the Nile Delta.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] When Moses first confronted the Egyptian king about the enslavement of the Israelites, Aaron served as his brother's spokesman to the Pharaoh.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Part of the Law given to Moses at Sinai granted Aaron the priesthood for himself and his male descendants, and he became the first High Priest of the Israelites.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Levitical priests or *kohanim* are traditionally believed and halakhically required to be of direct patrilineal descent from Aaron.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] According to the Book of Numbers, Aaron died at 123 years of age, on Mount Hor, in the fortieth year after the Israelites had come out of the land of Egypt.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Deuteronomy, however, places these events at Moseroth.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Thomas Römer argues the Pentateuch reflects unresolved tensions between Moses, Aaron, and the Levites, with Moses portrayed as dominant.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] According to the Book of Exodus, Aaron first functioned as Moses' assistant.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Because Moses complained that he could not speak well, God appointed Aaron as Moses' "prophet".
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] At the command of Moses, he let his rod turn into a snake.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Then he stretched out his rod in order to bring on the first three plagues.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] After that, Moses tended to act and speak for himself.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] During the journey in the wilderness, Aaron was not always prominent or active.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] At the battle with Amalek, he was chosen with Hur to support the hand of Moses that held the "rod of God".
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] When the revelation was given to Moses at Mount Sinai, he headed the elders of Israel who accompanied Moses on the way to the summit.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] While Joshua went with Moses to the top, however, Aaron and Hur remained below to look after the people.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] From here on in Exodus, Leviticus and Numbers, Joshua appears in the role of Moses' assistant while Aaron functions instead as the first high priest.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The books of Exodus, Leviticus and Numbers maintain that Aaron received from God a monopoly over the priesthood for himself and his male descendants.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The family of Aaron had the exclusive right and responsibility to make offerings on the altar to Yahweh.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The rest of his tribe, the Levites, were given subordinate responsibilities within the sanctuary.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Moses anointed and consecrated Aaron and his sons to the priesthood, and arrayed them in the robes of office.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] He also related to them God's detailed instructions for performing their duties while the rest of the Israelites listened.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Aaron and his successors as high priest were given control over the Urim and Thummim by which the will of God could be determined.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] God commissioned the Aaronide priests to distinguish the holy from the common and the clean from the unclean, and to teach the divine laws (the Torah) to the Israelites.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The priests were also commissioned to bless the people.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] In this way, the institution of the Aaronide priesthood was established.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] In later books of the Hebrew Bible, Aaron and his kin are not mentioned very often except in literature dating to the Babylonian captivity and later.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The books of Judges, Samuel and Kings mention priests and Levites, but do not mention the Aaronides in particular.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The Book of Ezekiel, which devotes much attention to priestly matters, calls the priestly upper class the Zadokites after one of King David's priests.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] It does reflect a two-tier priesthood with the Levites in subordinate position.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] A two-tier hierarchy of Aaronides and Levites appears in Ezra, Nehemiah and Chronicles.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] As a result, many historians think that Aaronide families did not control the priesthood in pre-exilic Israel.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] What is clear is that high priests claiming Aaronide descent dominated the Second Temple period.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Most scholars think the Torah reached its final form early in this period, which may account for Aaron's prominence in Exodus, Leviticus and Numbers.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Aaron plays a leading role in several stories of conflicts during Israel's wilderness wanderings.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] During the prolonged absence of Moses on Mount Sinai, the people provoked Aaron to make a golden calf.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] This incident nearly caused God to destroy the Israelites.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Moses successfully intervened, but then led the loyal Levites in executing many of the culprits; a plague afflicted those who were left.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Aaron, however, escaped punishment for his role in the affair, because of the intercession of Moses according to Deuteronomy 9:20.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Later retellings of this story almost always excuse Aaron for his role.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] For example, in rabbinic sources and in the Quran, Aaron was not the idol-maker and upon Moses' return begged his pardon because he felt mortally threatened by the Israelites.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] On the day of Aaron's consecration, his oldest sons, Nadab and Abihu, were burned up by divine fire because they offered "strange" incense.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Most interpreters think this story reflects a conflict between priestly families some time in Israel's past.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Others argue that the story simply shows what can happen if the priests do not follow God's instructions given through Moses.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The Torah generally depicts the siblings, Moses, Aaron, and Miriam, as the leaders of Israel after the Exodus, a view also reflected in the biblical Book of Micah.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Numbers 12, however, reports that on one occasion, Aaron and Miriam complained about Moses' exclusive claim to be the Lord's prophet.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Their presumption was rebuffed by God who affirmed Moses' uniqueness as the one with whom the Lord spoke face to face.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Miriam was punished with a skin disease (*tzaraath*) that turned her skin white.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Aaron pleaded with Moses to intercede for her, and Miriam, after seven days' quarantine, was healed.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Aaron once again escaped any retribution.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] According to Numbers 16–17, a Levite named Korah led many in challenging Aaron's exclusive claim to the priesthood.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] When the rebels were punished by being swallowed up by the earth, Eleazar, the son of Aaron, was commissioned to take charge of the censers of the dead priests.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] And when a plague broke out among the people who had sympathized with the rebels, Aaron, at the command of Moses, took his censer and stood between the living and the dead until the plague abated (Numbers 16:36, 17:1), atoning in the process.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] To emphasize the validity of the Levites' claim to the offerings and tithes of the Israelites, Moses collected a rod from the leaders of each tribe in Israel and laid the twelve rods overnight in the tent of meeting.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The next morning, Aaron's rod was found to have budded and blossomed and produced ripe almonds.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The rod was then placed before the Ark of the Covenant to symbolize Aaron's right to priesthood.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The following chapter then details the distinction between Aaron's family and the rest of the Levites: while all the Levites (and only Levites) were devoted to the care of the sanctuary, charge of its interior and the altar was committed to the Aaronites alone.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Aaron, like Moses, was not permitted to enter Canaan with the Israelites when Moses brought water out of a rock to quench the people's thirst.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Although they had been commanded to speak to the rock, Moses struck it with the staff twice, which was construed as displaying a lack of deference to the Lord.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] There are two accounts of the death of Aaron in the Torah.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Numbers says that soon after the incident at Meribah, Aaron with his son Eleazar and Moses ascended Mount Hor.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] There Moses stripped Aaron of his priestly garments and transferred them to Eleazar.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Aaron died on the summit of the mountain, and the people mourned him for thirty days.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The other account is found in Deuteronomy 10:6, where Aaron died at Moserah and was buried.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] There is a significant amount of travel between these two points, as the itinerary in Numbers 33:31–37 records seven stages between Moseroth (Mosera) and Mount Hor.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Aaron died on the 1st of Av and was 123 at the time of his death.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Aaron married Elisheba, daughter of Amminadab and sister of Nahshon of the tribe of Judah.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The sons of Aaron were Nadab, Abihu, Eleazar and Ithamar; only the latter two had progeny.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] A descendant of Aaron is an Aaronite, or Kohen, meaning Priest.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Any non-Aaronic Levite—i.e., descended from Levi but not from Aaron—assisted the Levitical priests of the family of Aaron in the care of the tabernacle; later of the temple.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The Gospel of Luke records that both Zechariah and Elizabeth and therefore their son John the Baptist were descendants of Aaron.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Jochebed is described as Levi's daughter, and thus her husband Amram's aunt, in the Book of Numbers (Numbers 26:59), the Masoretic Text of Exodus 6:20 and the Book of Jasher (Chapter 67, Verse 2-3).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] However, some manuscripts of the Septuagint Book of Exodus instead call her Amram's father's cousin, and others state that she was Amram's cousin.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Thomas Römer argues that external evidence and biblical texts suggest the Pentateuch reflects tensions among three groups: (1) a lay group aligned with Moses, (2) a priestly group linked to Aaron, and (3) the Levites.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] These tensions, particularly evident during the Persian and early Hellenistic periods, are seen in conflicting narratives concerning the roles of both Moses and Aaron.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Compromises are evident in texts like Exodus and Leviticus, where Moses and Aaron work together, though Moses is dominant.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Disagreements persisted, with some texts emphasizing Moses's superiority and others elevating Aaron's status.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The Pentateuch ultimately preserves these unresolved conflicts while portraying Moses as the unparalleled mediator of the Torah (Deut.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The older prophets and prophetical writers beheld in their priests the representatives of a religious form inferior to the prophetic truth; men without the spirit of God and lacking the willpower requisite to resist the multitude in its idolatrous proclivities.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Under the influence of the priesthood that shaped the destinies of the nation under Persian rule, a different ideal of the priest was formed, according to Malachi 2:4–7, and the prevailing tendency was to place Aaron on a footing equal with Moses.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] "At times Aaron, and at other times Moses, is mentioned first in Scripture—this is to show that they were of equal rank," says the Mekhilta of Rabbi Ishmael, which strongly implies this when introducing in its record of renowned men the glowing description of Aaron's ministration.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] In fulfillment of the promise of peaceful life, symbolized by the pouring of oil upon his head, Aaron's death, as described in the aggadah, was of a wonderful tranquility.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Accompanied by Moses, his brother, and by Eleazar, his son, Aaron went to the summit of Mount Hor, where the rock suddenly opened before him and a beautiful cave lit by a lamp presented itself to his view.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Moses said, "Take off thy priestly raiment and place it upon thy son Eleazar!" said Moses; "and then follow me." Aaron did as commanded; and they entered the cave, where was prepared a bed around which angels stood.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] "Go lie down upon thy bed, my brother," Moses continued; and Aaron obeyed without a murmur.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Then his soul departed as if by a kiss from God.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The cave closed behind Moses as he left; and he went down the hill with Eleazar, with garments rent, and crying: "Alas, Aaron, my brother! thou, the pillar of supplication of Israel!" When the Israelites cried in bewilderment, "Where is Aaron?" angels were seen carrying Aaron's bier through the air.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] A voice was then heard saying: "The law of truth was in his mouth, and iniquity was not found on his lips: he walked with me in righteousness, and brought many back from sin." He died on the first of Av.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The pillar of cloud which proceeded in front of Israel's camp disappeared at Aaron's death.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The rabbis particularly praise the brotherly sentiment between Aaron and Moses.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] When Moses was appointed ruler and Aaron high priest, neither betrayed any jealousy; instead they rejoiced in each other's greatness.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Again, mercy was personified in Aaron, according to Deuteronomy 33:8, and truth in Moses, according to Numbers 12:7.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] According to Tanhuma, Aaron's activity as a prophet began earlier than that of Moses.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] While Moses was stern and uncompromising, brooking no wrong, Aaron went about as peacemaker, reconciling man and wife when he saw them estranged, or a man with his neighbor when they quarreled, and winning evil-doers back into the right way by his friendly intercourse.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] As a result, Aaron's death was more intensely mourned than Moses': when Aaron died the whole house of Israel wept, including the women, while Moses was bewailed by "the sons of Israel" only.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Even in the making of the golden calf the rabbis find extenuating circumstances for Aaron.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] His fortitude and silent submission to the will of God on the loss of his two sons are referred to as an excellent example to men how to glorify God in the midst of great affliction.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] In the Eastern Orthodox and Maronite churches, Aaron is venerated as a saint whose feast day is shared with his brother Moses and celebrated on September 4.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] (Those churches that follow the traditional Julian calendar celebrate this day on September 17 of the modern Gregorian calendar).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Aaron is also commemorated with other Old Testament saints on the Sunday of the Holy Fathers, the Sunday before Christmas.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] In Eastern Orthodox Church he is commemorated on 20 July, 12 March, Sunday of the Forefathers, Sunday of the Fathers and on April 14 with all saint Sinai monks.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Aaron is commemorated as one of the Holy Forefathers in the Calendar of Saints of the Armenian Apostolic Church on July 30.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] He is commemorated on July 1 with an optional memorial in the General Roman Calendar, and in the Syriac Calendar.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The *Moses and Aaron Church* (Dutch: *Mozes en Aäronkerk*), in the Waterlooplein neighborhood of Amsterdam, is one of the most well-known Catholic churches in the city.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] One version of the Bible has an encyclopedia that describes Aaron's role in Scripture as the "spokesman for Moses".
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] In the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, the Aaronic priesthood is the lesser order of priesthood under the higher order of the Melchizedek priesthood.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Those ordained to this priesthood have the authority to act in God's name in certain responsibilities in the church such as the administration of the sacrament and baptism.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] In the Community of Christ, the Aaronic order of priesthood is regarded as an appendage to the Melchisedec order, and consists of the priesthood offices of deacon, teacher, and priest.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] While differing in responsibilities, these offices, along with those of the Melchisidec order, are regarded as equal before God.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Aaron (Arabic: هارون, *Hārūn*) is mentioned in the Quran as a prophet of God.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The Quran praises Aaron repeatedly, calling him a "believing servant" as well as one who was "guided" and one of the "victors".
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The Quran additionally denies the role of Aaron in the creation of the golden calf, attributing the action to Samiri.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Aaron is important in Islam for his role in the events of the Exodus, in which, according to the Quran and Islamic belief, he preached with his younger brother, Musa (Moses) to the Pharaoh of the Exodus.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Aaron's significance in Islam, however, is not limited to his role as the helper of Moses.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Islamic tradition also accords Aaron the role of a patriarch, as tradition records that the priestly descent came through Aaron's lineage, which included the entire House of Amran.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] In the Baháʼí Faith, although his father is described as both an apostle and a prophet, Aaron is merely described as a prophet.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] The *Kitáb-i-Íqán* describes Imran as his father.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Aaron appears paired with Moses frequently in Jewish and Christian art, especially in the illustrations of manuscript and printed Bibles.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] He can usually be distinguished by his priestly vestments, especially his turban or miter and jeweled breastplate.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] He frequently holds a censer or, sometimes, his flowering rod.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Aaron also appears in scenes depicting the wilderness Tabernacle and its altar, as already in the third-century frescos in the synagogue at Dura-Europos in Syria.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] An eleventh-century portable silver altar from Fulda, Germany depicts Aaron with his censor, and is located in the Musée de Cluny in Paris.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] This is also how he appears in the frontispieces of early printed Passover Haggadot and occasionally in church sculptures.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Aaron has rarely been the subject of portraits, such as those by Anton Kern [1710–1747] and by Pier Francesco Mola [c.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Christian artists sometimes portray Aaron as a prophet holding a scroll, as in a twelfth-century sculpture from the Cathedral of Noyon in the Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York and often in Eastern Orthodox icons.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Illustrations of the Golden Calf story usually include him as well – most notably in Nicolas Poussin's *The Adoration of the Golden Calf* (c.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Finally, some artists interested in validating later priesthoods have painted the ordination of Aaron and his sons (Leviticus 8).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Harry Anderson's realistic portrayal is often reproduced in the literature of the Latter Day Saints.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/aaron] Aaron has been depicted in Exodus-related drama, such as *The Ten Commandments* (1956) and *Exodus: Gods and Kings* (2014).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-bulrushes] The **ark of bulrushes** (Hebrew: תבת גמא, romanized: *têḇaṯ gōme*) was a container which, according to the episode known as the finding of Moses in the biblical Book of Exodus, carried the infant Moses.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-bulrushes] The ark, containing the three-month-old baby Moses, was placed in reeds by the river bank (presumably the Nile) to protect him from the Egyptian mandate to drown every male Hebrew child, and discovered there by Pharaoh's daughter.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-bulrushes] The ark is described as being daubed with asphalt and pitch, and the English word "ark" is a translation of the Hebrew תֵּבָה (*tevah*, modern *teiva*), the same word used for Noah's Ark.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-bulrushes] Tigay, the word *tevah* is probably derived from the Egyptian word *tbỉ*, which refers to a "box" or "coffin".
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-bulrushes] Irving Finkel also notes similarities between the Biblical Hebrew term and the nearly identical Babylonian word for an oblong boat, *ṭubbû*.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-bulrushes] The "bulrushes" (Hebrew: גֹּ֫מֶא *gome*) were likely to have been papyrus stalks daubed with bitumen and pitch.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-bulrushes] A similar but earlier story is told of Sargon of Akkad.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The **Ark of the Covenant**, also known as the **Ark of the Testimony** or the **Ark of God**, was a religious storage chest and relic held to be the most sacred object by the Israelites.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Religious tradition describes it as a wooden storage chest decorated in solid gold accompanied by an ornamental lid known as the Seat of Mercy.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] According to the Book of Exodus and First Book of Kings in the Hebrew Bible and the Old Testament, the Ark contained the Tablets of the Law by which God delivered the Ten Commandments to Moses at Mount Sinai.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] According to the Book of Exodus, the Book of Numbers, and the Epistle to the Hebrews in the New Testament, it also contained Aaron's rod and a pot of manna.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The biblical account relates that approximately one year after the Israelites' exodus from Egypt, the Ark was created according to the pattern that God gave to Moses when the Israelites were encamped at the foot of Mount Sinai.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Thereafter, the gold-plated acacia chest's staves were lifted and carried by the Levites approximately 2,000 cubits (800 meters or 2,600 feet) in advance of the people while they marched.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] God spoke with Moses "from between the two cherubim" on the Ark's cover.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Jewish tradition holds various views on the Ark's fate, including that it was taken to Babylon, hidden by King Josiah in the Temple or underground chambers, or concealed by Jeremiah in a cave on Mount Nebo.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The Ethiopian Orthodox Church asserts it is housed in Axum; the Lemba people of southern Africa claim ancestral possession with a replica in Zimbabwe; some traditions say it was in Rome or Ireland but lost, though no verified evidence conclusively confirms its location today.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] It is honored by Samaritans, symbolized in Christianity as a type of Christ and the Virgin Mary, mentioned in the Quran, and viewed with spiritual significance in the Baháʼí Faith.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The Ark of the Covenant has been prominently featured in modern films such as *Raiders of the Lost Ark* and other literary and artistic works, often depicted as a powerful and mysterious relic with both historical and supernatural significance.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] There are ongoing academic discussions among biblical scholars and archeologists regarding the history of the Ark's movements around the Ancient Near East as well as the history and dating of the Ark narratives in the Hebrew Bible.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] There is additional scholarly debate over possible historical influences that led to the creation of the Ark, including Bedouin or Egyptian influences.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] According to the Book of Exodus, God instructed Moses to build the Ark during his 40-day stay upon Mount Sinai.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] He was shown the pattern for the tabernacle and furnishings of the Ark, and told that it would be made of shittim wood (also known as acacia wood) to house the Tablets of Stone.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Moses instructed Bezalel and Oholiab to construct the Ark.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The Book of Exodus gives detailed instructions on how the Ark is to be constructed.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] It is to be 2+1⁄2 cubits in length, 1+1⁄2 cubits breadth, and 1+1⁄2 cubits height (approximately 131×79×79 cm or 52×31×31 in) of acacia wood.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Then it is to be gilded entirely with gold, and a crown or molding of gold is to be put around it.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Four rings of gold are to be attached to its four corners, two on each side—and through these rings staves of shittim wood overlaid with gold for carrying the Ark are to be inserted; and these are not to be removed.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The biblical account continues that, after its creation by Moses, the Ark was carried by the Israelites during their 40 years of wandering in the desert.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Whenever the Israelites camped, the Ark was placed in the tent of meeting, inside the Tabernacle.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] When the Israelites, led by Joshua toward the Promised Land, arrived at the banks of the River Jordan, the Ark was carried in the lead, preceding the people, and was the signal for their advance.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] During the crossing, the river grew dry as soon as the feet of the priests carrying the Ark touched its waters, and remained so until the priests—with the Ark—left the river after the people had passed over.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] As memorials, twelve stones were taken from the Jordan at the place where the priests had stood.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] During the Battle of Jericho, the Ark was carried around the city once a day for six days, preceded by the armed men and seven priests sounding seven trumpets of rams' horns.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] On the seventh day, the seven priests sounding the seven trumpets of rams' horns before the Ark compassed the city seven times, and, with a great shout, Jericho's wall fell down flat and the people took the city.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] After the defeat at Ai, Joshua lamented before the Ark.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] When Joshua read the Law to the people between Mount Gerizim and Mount Ebal, they stood on each side of the Ark.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The Ark was then kept at Shiloh after the Israelites finished their conquest of Canaan.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] We next hear of the Ark in Bethel, where it was being cared for by the priest Phinehas, the grandson of Aaron.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] According to this verse, it was consulted by the people of Israel when they were planning to attack the Benjaminites at the Battle of Gibeah.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Later the Ark was kept at Shiloh again, where it was cared for by Hophni and Phinehas, two sons of Eli.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] According to the biblical narrative, a few years later the elders of Israel decided to take the Ark onto the battlefield to assist them against the Philistines, having recently been defeated at the battle of Eben-Ezer.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] They were again heavily defeated, with the loss of 30,000 men.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The Ark was captured by the Philistines, and Hophni and Phinehas were killed.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The news of its capture was at once taken to Shiloh by a messenger "with his clothes rent, and with earth upon his head".
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The old priest, Eli, fell dead when he heard it, and his daughter-in-law, bearing a son at the time the news of the Ark's capture was received, named him Ichabod—explained as "The glory has departed Israel" in reference to the loss of the Ark.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The Philistines took the Ark to several places in their country, and at each place misfortune befell them.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] At Ashdod it was placed in the temple of Dagon.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The next morning Dagon was found prostrate, bowed down, before it; and on being restored to his place, he was on the following morning again found prostrate and broken.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The people of Ashdod were smitten with tumors; a plague of rodents was sent over the land.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The affliction of tumours was also visited upon the people of Gath and of Ekron, whither the Ark was successively removed.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] After the Ark had been among them for seven months, the Philistines, on the advice of their diviners, returned it to the Israelites, accompanying its return with an offering consisting of golden images of the tumors and mice wherewith they had been afflicted.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The Ark was set up in the field of Joshua of Beit Shemesh, and the people of Beit Shemesh offered sacrifices and burnt offerings according to the first five verses of 1 Samuel 6.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Verse 19, 1 Samuel 6 states that out of curiosity, the people of Beit Shemesh gazed at the Ark, and as a punishment, God struck down seventy of them (fifty thousand and seventy in some translations).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The men of Beit Shemesh sent to Kiriath-Jearim to have the Ark removed in verse 21, and it was taken to the house of Abinadab, whose son Eleazar was sanctified to keep it.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Kiriath-Jearim remained the abode of the Ark for twenty years, according to 1 Samuel 7.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Under Saul, the Ark was with the army before he first met the Philistines, but the king was too impatient to consult it before engaging in battle.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] In 1 Chronicles 13, it is stated that the people were not accustomed to consulting the Ark in the days of Saul.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] In the biblical narrative, at the beginning of his reign over the United Monarchy, King David removed the Ark from Kirjath-jearim amid great rejoicing.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] On the way to Zion, Uzzah, one of the drivers of the cart that carried the Ark, put out his hand to steady the Ark, and was struck dead by God for touching it.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The place was subsequently named "Perez-Uzzah", literally 'outburst against Uzzah', as a result.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] David, in fear, carried the Ark aside into the house of Obed-edom the Gittite, instead of carrying it on to Zion, and it stayed there for three months.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] In Zion, David put the Ark in the tent he had prepared for it, offered sacrifices, distributed food, and blessed the people and his own household.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] David used the tent as a personal place of prayer.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The Levites were appointed to minister before the Ark.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] David's plan of building a temple for the Ark was stopped on the advice of the prophet Nathan.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The Ark was with the army during the siege of Rabbah; and when David fled from Jerusalem at the time of Absalom's conspiracy, the Ark was carried along with him until he ordered Zadok the priest to return it to Jerusalem.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] According to the Biblical narrative, when Abiathar was dismissed from the priesthood by King Solomon for having taken part in Adonijah's conspiracy against David, his life was spared because he had formerly borne the Ark.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Solomon worshipped before the Ark after his dream in which God promised him wisdom.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] During the construction of Solomon's Temple, a special inner room, named *Kodesh Hakodashim* ('Holy of Holies'), was prepared to receive and house the Ark; and when the Temple was dedicated, the Ark—containing the original tablets of the Ten Commandments—was placed therein.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] When the priests emerged from the holy place after placing the Ark there, the Temple was filled with a cloud, "for the glory of the Lord had filled the house of the Lord".
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] When Solomon married Pharaoh's daughter, he caused her to dwell in a house outside Zion, as Zion was consecrated because it contained the Ark.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] King Josiah also had the Ark returned to the Temple, from which it appears to have been removed by one of his predecessors (cf.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] In a noncanonical text known as the Treatise of the Vessels, Hezekiah is identified as one of the kings who had the Ark and the other treasures of Solomon's Temple hidden during a time of crisis.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] To many scholars, Hezekiah is also credited as having written all or some of the Book of Kohelet (Ecclesiastes in the Christian tradition), in particular the famously enigmatic epilogue.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Notably, the epilogue appears to refer to the Ark story with references to almond blossoms (i.e., Aaron's rod), locusts, silver, and gold.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The epilogue then cryptically refers to a pitcher broken at a fountain and a wheel broken at a cistern.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Although scholars disagree on whether the Pool of Siloam's pure spring waters were used by pilgrims for ritual purification, many scholars agree that a stepped pilgrimage road between the pool and the Temple had been built in the first century CE.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] This roadway has been partially excavated, but the west side of the Pool of Siloam remained unexcavated, as of 2016.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] In Rabbinic literature, the final disposition of the Ark is disputed.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Some rabbis hold that it must have been carried off to Babylon, while others hold that it must have been hidden lest it be carried off into Babylon and never brought back.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] A late 2nd-century rabbinic work known as the *Tosefta* states the opinions of these rabbis that Josiah, the king of Judah, stored away the Ark, along with the jar of manna, and a jar containing the holy anointing oil, the rod of Aaron which budded and a chest given to Israel by the Philistines.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The Kohathites were one of the Levite houses from the Book of Numbers.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] They had the responsibility to care for "the most holy things" in the tabernacle.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The Talmud in Yoma suggests that the Ark was removed from the Temple towards the end of the era of the First Temple and the Second Temple never housed it.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] According to one view, it was taken to Babylon when Nebuchadnezzar conquered Jerusalem in 587 BCE, exiling King Jeconiah along with the upper classes.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Another perspective proposes that Josiah, king of Judah, hid the Ark in anticipation of the Temple's destruction.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] One account in the Talmud mentions a priest's suspicion of a tampered stone in a chamber designated for wood storage, hinting at the Ark's concealment.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Alternatively, it has been suggested that the Ark remained underground in the Holy of Holies.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Some of the Chazal, including the Radak and Maimonides, propose that Solomon designed tunnels beneath the Temple to safeguard the Ark that Josiah later used.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Attempts to excavate this area have yielded little due to political sensitivities.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] An opinion found in the II Maccabees 2:4-10, asserts that Jeremiah hid the Ark and other sacred items in a cave on Mount Nebo (now in Jordan), anticipating the Neo-Babylonian invasion.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Archaeological evidence shows strong cultic activity at Kiriath-Jearim in the 8th and 7th centuries BC, well after the ark was supposedly removed from there to Jerusalem.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] In particular, archaeologists found a large elevated podium, associated with the Northern Kingdom and not the Southern Kingdom, which may have been a shrine.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Thomas Römer suggests that this may indicate that the ark was not moved to Jerusalem until much later, possibly during the reign of King Josiah (reigned c.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] He notes that this might explain why the ark featured prominently in the history before Solomon, but not after.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Additionally, 2 Chronicles 35:3 indicates that it was moved during King Josiah's reign.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] However, Yigal Levin argues that there is no evidence that Kiriath-Jearim was a cultic center in the monarchical era or that it ever housed any "temple of the Ark".
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Sparks believes the story of the Ark was written independently around the 8th century BC in a text referred to as the "Ark Narrative" and then incorporated into the main biblical narrative just before the Babylonian exile.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Römer also suggests that the ark may have carried sacred stones "of the kind found in the chests of pre-Islamic Bedouins" and speculates that these may have been either a statue of Yahweh or a pair of statues depicting both Yahweh and his companion goddess Asherah.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] In contrast, Scott Noegel has argued that the parallels between the ark and these practices remain "unconvincing" in part because the Bedouin objects lack the ark's distinctive structure, function, and mode of transportation.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Noegel suggests that the ancient Egyptian Solar barque is a more plausible model for the Israelite ark, since Egyptian barques had all the features just mentioned.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] He adds that the Egyptians also were known to place written covenants beneath the feet of statues, proving a further parallel to the placement of the covenantal tablets inside the ark.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Levin holds that some biblical texts suggest that the Ark of the Covenant was only one among many other different arks at regional shrines prior to the centralization of worship in Jerusalem, although Raanan Eichler disagrees.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] While Clifford Mark McCormick has questioned whether the Ark ever existed, other scholars such as Eichler, David A.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Hemmings have defended its historicity and antiquity based on linguistic evidence and significant parallels with similar artifacts from New Kingdom Egypt.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The Ark is first mentioned in the Book of Exodus and then numerous times in Deuteronomy, Joshua, Judges, I Samuel, II Samuel, I Kings, I Chronicles, II Chronicles, Psalms, and Jeremiah.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The "mountain from the top of which Moses saw God's promised land" would be Mount Nebo, located in what is now Jordan.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Samaritan tradition claims that the Ark of the Covenant had been kept at a sanctuary on Mt.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] In the New Testament, the Ark is mentioned in the Letter to the Hebrews and the Revelation to St.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] In the Gospel of Luke, the author's accounts of the Annunciation and Visitation are constructed using eight points of literary parallelism to compare Mary to the Ark.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The contents of the ark were seen by Church Fathers including Thomas Aquinas as symbolic of the attributes of Jesus Christ: the manna as the Holy Eucharist; Aaron's rod as Jesus' eternal priestly authority; and the tablets of the Law, as the Lawgiver himself.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Thomas Aquinas compared the two types of materials of the ark to the two natures of Christ in the hypostatic union (Jesus having human and divine natures).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] He wrote, "The Ark, wherein were the Law and the manna, signified Christ, who is 'the living bread that came down from Heaven' and 'the fulfillment of the Law'.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Catholic scholars connect the pregnant, birthing Woman of the Apocalypse from Revelation 12:1-2, with the Blessed Virgin Mary, whom they identify as the "Ark of the New Covenant." Carrying the saviour of mankind within her, she herself became the Holy of Holies.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] This is the interpretation given in the third century by Gregory Thaumaturgus, and in the fourth century by Saint Ambrose, Saint Ephraem of Syria and Saint Augustine.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The Catechism of the Catholic Church teaches that Mary is a metaphorical version of the ark: "Mary, in whom the Lord himself has just made his dwelling, is the daughter of Zion in person, the ark of the covenant, the place where the glory of the Lord dwells.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Saint Athanasius, the bishop of Alexandria, is credited with writing about the connections between the Ark and the Virgin Mary: "O noble Virgin, truly you are greater than any other greatness.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] For who is your equal in greatness, O dwelling place of God the Word?
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] To whom among all creatures shall I compare you, O Virgin?
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] You are greater than them all O (Ark of the) Covenant, clothed with purity instead of gold!
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] You are the Ark in which is found the golden vessel containing the true manna, that is, the flesh in which Divinity resides" (*Homily of the Papyrus of Turin*).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] According to Uri Rubin, the Ark of the Covenant has a religious basis in Islam (and the Baháʼí Faith), which gives it special significance.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church claims to possess the Ark of the Covenant in Axum.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The Ark is kept under guard in a treasury near the Church of Our Lady Mary of Zion.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Replicas of the tablets within the Ark, or *tabots*, are kept in every Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Each tabot is kept in its own holy of holies, each with its own dedication to a particular saint; the most popular of these include Saint Mary, Saint George and Saint Michael.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The *Kebra Nagast* is often said to have been composed to legitimise the Solomonic dynasty, which ruled the Ethiopian Empire following its establishment in 1270, but this is not the case.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] It was originally composed in some other language (Coptic or Greek), then translated into Arabic, and translated into Geʽez in 1321.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] It narrates how the Ark of the Covenant was brought to Ethiopia by Menelik I with divine assistance, while a forgery was left in the Temple in Jerusalem.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Although the *Kebra Nagast* is the best-known account of this belief, the belief predates the document.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Abu al-Makarim, writing in the last quarter of the twelfth century, makes one early reference to this belief that they possessed the Ark.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Describing the ark there, he says, "They have a wooden box, but it's empty.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] On 25 June 2009, the patriarch of the Orthodox Church of Ethiopia, Abune Paulos, said he would announce to the world the next day the unveiling of the Ark of the Covenant, which he said had been kept safe and secure in a church in Axum.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The following day, he announced that he would not unveil the Ark after all, but that instead he could attest to its current status.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The Lemba people of South Africa and Zimbabwe have claimed that their ancestors carried the Ark south, calling it the *ngoma lungundu* "voice of God", eventually hiding it in a deep cave in the Dumghe mountains, their spiritual home.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] On 14 April 2008, in a UK Channel 4 documentary, Tudor Parfitt, taking a literalist approach to the Biblical story, described his research into this claim.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] He says that the object described by the Lemba has attributes similar to the Ark.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] It was of similar size, was carried on poles by priests, was not allowed to touch the ground, was revered as a voice of their God, and was used as a weapon of great power, sweeping enemies aside.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] In his book *The Lost Ark of the Covenant* (2008), Parfitt also suggests that the Ark was taken to Arabia following the events depicted in the Second Book of Maccabees, and cites Arabic sources which maintain it was brought in distant times to Yemen.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Genetic Y-DNA analyses in the 2000s have established a partially Middle-Eastern origin for a portion of the male Lemba population but no specific Jewish connection.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Lemba tradition maintains that the Ark spent some time in a place called Sena, which might be Sena, Yemen.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Later, it was taken across the sea to East Africa and may have been taken inland at the time of Great Zimbabwe.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] According to their oral traditions, it self-destructed sometime after the Lemba's arrival with the Ark.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Using a core from the original, the Lemba priests constructed a new one.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] This replica was discovered in a cave by a Swedish-German missionary named Harald Philip Hans von Sicard in the 1940s and eventually found its way to the Museum of Human Sciences in Harare.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The 2nd century Rabbi Eliezer ben Jose claimed that he saw somewhere in Rome the mercy-seat lid of the ark.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Accordingly, another tale claims that the Ark was kept within the Basilica of Saint John Lateran, surviving the pillages of Rome by King of the Visigoths Alaric I and King of the Vandals Gaiseric but was eventually lost when the basilica burned in the fifth century.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Between 1899 and 1902, the British-Israel Association of London carried out limited excavations of the Hill of Tara in Ireland looking for the Ark of the Covenant.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Irish nationalists, including Maud Gonne and the Royal Society of Antiquaries of Ireland (RSAI), campaigned successfully to have them stopped before they destroyed the hill.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] A non-invasive survey by archaeologist Conor Newman carried out from 1992 until 1995 found no evidence of the Ark.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The British Israelites believed that the Ark was located at the grave of the Egyptian princess Tea Tephi, who according to Irish legend came to Ireland in the 6th century BC and married Irish King Érimón.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Because of the historical importance of Tara, Irish nationalists like Douglas Hyde and W.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Yeats voiced their protests in newspapers, and in 1902 Maud Gonne led a campaign against the excavations at the site.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Many Malaitans claim that the ark of covenant is buried somewhere deep in the jungle of their island.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] They have a family tradition that they are a lost Jewish tribe from Zedekiah the high priest of Israel.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] And that he came there in the year 66 AD to bury it.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] This idea has been recently presented in the article “Ark of Covenant Location Discovered!” by Mike Edery.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] In the article, he argues that a Torah code from the Baal Shem Tov reveals its current location on Malaita island.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Additionally in the year 2013, a journalist by the name of Mathew Fishbane had visited the island in the hopes of finding the ark on Malaita island.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] He interviewed several Malaitans who gave the story of how the ark ended up there.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Although he was unable to find it, the legend still lives on today.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Philip Kaufman conceived of the Ark of the Covenant as the main plot device of Steven Spielberg's 1981 adventure film *Raiders of the Lost Ark*, where it is found by Indiana Jones in the Egyptian city of Tanis in 1936.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] In the Danish family film *The Lost Treasure of the Knights Templar* from 2006, the main part of the treasure found in the end is the Ark of the Covenant.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The power of the Ark comes from static electricity stored in separated metal plates like a giant Leyden jar.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] In Harry Turtledove's novel *Alpha and Omega* (2019) the ark is found by archeologists, and the characters have to deal with the proven existence of God.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] The Ark has been depicted many times in art for two thousand years, some examples are in the article above, a few more are here.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/ark-of-the-covenant] Yom HaAliyah (Aliyah Day) (Hebrew: יום העלייה) is an Israeli national holiday celebrated annually on the tenth of the Hebrew month of Nisan to commemorate the Israelites crossing the Jordan River into the Land of Israel while carrying the Ark of the Covenant.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] The figurine may have been held by women in childbirth.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] An **Asherah pole** is a sacred tree or pole that stood near Canaanite religious locations to honor the goddess Asherah.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] The relation of the literary references to an *asherah* and archaeological finds of Judaean pillar-figurines has engendered a literature of debate.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] The **asherim** (the Hebrew plural form) were also cult objects related to the worship of Asherah, the consort of either Ba'al or, as inscriptions from Kuntillet ‘Ajrud and Khirbet el-Qom attest, Yahweh, and thus objects of contention among competing cults.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] Most English translations of the Hebrew Bible translate *asherim* (Biblical Hebrew: אֲשֵׁרִים, romanized: *ăšērim* or אֲשֵׁרוֹת *ăšēroṯ*) to "Asherah poles".
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] Asherim are mentioned in the Hebrew Bible in the books of Exodus, Deuteronomy, Judges, the Books of Kings, the second Book of Chronicles, and the books of Isaiah, Jeremiah, and Micah.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] Scholars have indicated that the plural use of the term provides ample evidence that reference is being made to objects of worship rather than a transcendent figure.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] The Hebrew Bible suggests that the poles were made of wood.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] In the sixth chapter of the Book of Judges, God is recorded as instructing the shophet Gideon to cut down an Asherah pole that was next to an altar to Baal.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] The wood was to be used for a burnt offering.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] For example, King Manasseh of Judah placed an Asherah pole in Solomon's Temple (2 Kings 21:7).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] King Josiah's reforms in the late 7th century BC included the destruction of many Asherah poles (2 Kings 23:14).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] Biblical archaeologists have suggested that until the 6th century BC the Israelite peoples had household shrines, or at least figurines, of Asherah, which are strikingly common in the archaeological remains.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] Taylor suggests the temple menorah’s iconography can be traced to representations of a sacred tree, possibly “based on the form of an asherah, perhaps one associated in particular with Bethel.” However, Rachel Hachlili finds this hypothesis unlikely.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] Raphael Patai identified the pillar figurines with Asherah in *The Hebrew Goddess*.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] So far, the purpose of Asherah poles is unknown.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] Due to their role in Iron Age Yahwism, some suggest they were embodiments of Yahweh himself.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] Evidence for this includes pro-Yahwist kings like Jehu not destroying Asherah poles, despite violently suppressing non-Yahwist cults.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] In addition, the Yahwist inscription of *Kuntillet ʿAjrud* in the Sinai Peninsula pairs Yahweh with Asherah.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] Scholars believe Asherah is merely a cultic object or temple, but others argue that it is a generic name for any consort of Yahweh.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] Ronald Hendel argues a middle ground is possible, where the Asherah pole is a symbol of the eponymous goddess, but is believed to be the mediator between the worshipper and Yahweh, where she becomes the "effective bestower of blessing".
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] Stéphanie Anthonioz says that early references to Asherah poles in the Hebrew Bible (i.e.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] Deuteronomy 16:21–22) were built on the awareness that Yahweh had a consort, from the perspective of many Israelites.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] With the exception of Deuteronomists, many Near Easterners believed symbols and cult images, like the Asherah pole, were reflections of the divine and the divine themselves in their anthropomorphized forms.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] Agrarian and hunter-gatherer societies had a need to keep track of the seasons for survival purposes, to predict when to move, or plant and harvest.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] The earliest systems for tracking seasonal change was a simple pole or tall, narrow rock installed at the highest open hill or open plain, with a semi-circle of similar poles or stones to track the shadow of the sun throughout the year to determine solar solstices.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] These structures eventually took on additional meanings and became places of social gatherings and events, to include religious worship and sacrifice throughout the millennia.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/asherah-pole] In some locales this led to what became later known as Asherah.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] Because of the mountain's importance in the Biblical narrative and location, *Zephon* (Hebrew: צפון, romanized: *ṣap̄on*) came to metonymously signify "north" in Hebrew.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] The name is, therefore, sometimes given in translation as **Lord of the North**.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] Baʿal Zephon was equated with the Greek god **Zeus Kasios** and later with the Roman **Jupiter Casius**.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] Because Baʿal Zephon was considered a protector of maritime trade, sanctuaries were constructed in his honor around the Mediterranean Sea by his Canaanite and Phoenician devotees.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] "Baal-zephon" thereby became a placename—most notably mentioned in the Book of Exodus as the location where the miraculous Passage of the Red Sea happened during the Exodus.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] The name Baʿal Zaphon never appears in the mythological texts discovered at Ugarit.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] Instead, it occurs in guides to ritual and in letters, where it is used to differentiate this form of Baʿal from others such as Baʿal Ugarit.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] The iconography of a storm god standing on two mountains is associated with him.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] The earliest discovered depiction of the god – where he stands astride two mountains in a smiting posture (a posture associated with Baal in general) – dates to the 18th century BC.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] Other depictions show him crowned and bearing a scepter.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] As a protector of maritime trade, his temples also received votive stone anchors.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] The treaty between Asarhaddon and King Baʿal of Tyre ranks Baʿal Zaphon third behind Baʿal Shamem and Baʿal Malage.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] In addition to his temple at Jebel Aqra and Ugarit, Baʿal Zaphon is known to have been worshipped at Tyre and Carthage and served as the chief god of the colony at Tahpanes.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] A 14th-century letter from the king of Ugarit to the Egyptian pharaoh (KTU2 2.23) places Baʿal Zaphon as equivalent to Amun.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] Temples to Zeus Kasios are attested in Egypt, Athens, Epidauros, Delos, Corfu, Sicily, and Spain, with the last mention occurring on Rome's German border in the 3rd century.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] 1st-millennium BC Assyrian texts mention Baʿal Zaphon as the name of the mountain itself.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] Locally, this mountain was worshipped in its own right.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] Gmirkin identified this as Arsinoe on the Gulf of Suez.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] A Ptolemaic-era geographical text at the Cairo Museum lists four border fortresses, the third being "Midgol and Baʿal Zaphon".
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] In context, it appears to have been located on a route to the Red Sea coast, perhaps on the canal from Pithom to a location near Arsinoe.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] Falk has noted that Baal-zephon is mentioned in *Papyrus Sallier IV* as an ancient Egyptian place, which was probably located northeast of the Wadi Tumilat.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] According to Herodotus (who considered it to mark the boundary between Egypt and Syria), at Ras Kouroun, a small mountain near the marshy Lake Bardawil, the "Serbonian Bog" of Herodotus, where Zeus' ancient opponent Typhon was "said to be hidden".
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] Here, Greeks knew, Baal Sephon was worshipped.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] The only instance where the Canaanite god is depicted in both image and language is a wholly Egyptian work featuring Ba'al Zephon.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] Eythan Levy notes a parallel between Ba'al Zephon and the "Asiatic Seth." Seth's attributes are horns, an ankh in one hand, a was sceptre in the other, and a beard.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] He wears a conical hat resembling the white crown of Egypt with a long string ending in a tassel that looks like a lotus flower.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/baal-zephon] Ba'al here seems to be depicted largely the same way.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] The **Battle of Rephidim**, as described in the Bible, took place between the Israelites and the Amalekites, which occurred in Rephidim while the former were moving towards the Promised Land.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] The description of this battle can be found in the Book of Exodus.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] According to Exodus 17:8–13, following the Israelites' escape from Egypt they camped in Rephidim.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] The battle began with the Amalekites' unprovoked attack against the Israelites (Exodus 17:8).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] Afterwards, Yahweh announced the extermination of the Amalekites and called on Israel to defeat them, stating that Israel would experience peace with their enemies (Exodus 17:14, Deuteronomy 25:19).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] This was the first of several conflicts over several hundred years between the Amalekites and Israelites.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] Moses urged the faithful to fight and placed his people under the leadership of Joshua.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] The words, "that will hold up the rod of God," could be an expression of his beliefs about impending victory in the coming battle, since they fought under the banner of God.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] When he held his hands up, Israel gained the military advantage.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] Whenever he put his hands down, according to the Biblical account, they began to lose.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] The Bible describes how when Moses became tired, his closest relatives, Hur and Aaron, held up his hands for support (Exodus 17:12).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] The battle lasted until the evening, ending in victory for the Israelites.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] The Book of Exodus mentions the curse-punishment thrown at enemies of the chosen people, the children of Israel.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] The Amalekites were to be erased from history.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] Curses with similar overtones are also recorded in the Book of Jeremiah (Jer 2:3).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] After the success of the Israelite military, they erected an altar – Yahweh-nissi (Heb. יְהוָה נִסִּי) – denoting "The Lord is my banner." The name refers to the sticks held by Moses.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] Midrashic sources provide other, finer details of the prelude to the battle and the battle itself.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] The Amalekites, who were fair skinned, colored their faces with soot and donned Canaanite armor to disguise themselves in order to disrupt the prayers of the Israelites, who would pray to be rescued from their (nonexistent) Canaanite attackers.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] They pursued the stragglers of the Israelite's Horde and sodomized, castrated, and killed them, flinging their penises into the camp of the Israelites as a derision of their circumcision.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] Eventually, they ran out of stragglers to kill, and began to harass the Israelites within the encampment, using arrows, stones and javelins, which were ineffective, as they could not penetrate the Clouds of Glory about the camp.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] It was prophetically revealed to Moses that the attackers were Amalekites, not Canaanites, and thus he ordered Joshua to deal with them militarily.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] According to some researchers, Rephidim was the only oasis in the region.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] It was situated in the mountains where nomads brought cattle to drink.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] When the Israelites traveled into Canaan, they discovered the Amalekites, who inhabited the northern Sinai Peninsula and the Negev.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] According to William Petri, Amalekites tried to prevent the Israelites from reaching the oasis.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] Petri's conclusions are based on his research on climate, which, since the days of Moses, remained almost unchanged.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] Therefore, he concluded that the number of nomads living there for millennia remained at a similar level, around five to seven thousand people.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] Taking into account the biblical description of the battle, and the description that its outcome was not decided until the evening, the number of combatants on both sides are assumed to have been close.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] It is understood that the Israelites had around six hundred thousand families.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] The clash resulted in the intruders accessing the oasis.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] Nineteenth-century Bible scholar and commentator Alexander Łopuchin, interpreted Deuteronomy (Deuteronomy 25:17–18) to mean that the Amalekites first laid siege, robbing exhausted travelers who lagged behind the oasis, and then attacked an entire tribe of Israelites.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] John Van Seters argues that, according to traditional interpretation, a show of hands by Moses was regarded as a sign of prayer; this is significant because the text does not directly mention prayer.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] Van Seters believed that Moses' gesture, like Joshua's – elevating the javelin (Joshua 8:18–26) – should be understood as the practice of magic, and secondarily as religious.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] Hans-Christoph Schmitt disputes this view, pointing out that such restrictions would be unlikely.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/battle-of-refidim] In his opinion, parallels should be sought in 1 Samuel 7:2–13, where Israel is victorious thanks to the constant prayer of Samuel.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The parashah is made up of 6,423 Hebrew letters, 1,681 Hebrew words, 116 verses, and 216 lines in a Torah Scroll (*Sefer Torah*).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] Jews read it the sixteenth Sabbath after Simchat Torah, in January or February.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] As the parashah describes God's deliverance of the Israelites from Egypt, Jews also read part of the parashah, Exodus 13:17–15:26, as the initial Torah reading for the seventh day of Passover.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] And Jews also read the part of the parashah about Amalek, Exodus 17:8–16, on Purim, which commemorates the story of Esther and the Jewish people's victory over Haman's plan to kill the Jews, told in the book of Esther.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] Esther 3:1 identifies Haman as an Agagite, and thus a descendant of Amalek.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] Numbers 24:7 identifies the Agagites with the Amalekites.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] A midrash tells that between King Agag's capture by Saul and his killing by Samuel, Agag fathered a child, from whom Haman in turn descended.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The parashah is notable for the Song of the Sea, which is traditionally chanted using a different melody and is written by the scribe using a distinctive brick-like pattern in the Torah scroll.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The Sabbath when it is read is known as Shabbat Shirah, as the Song of the Sea is sometimes known as the Shirah (song).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] Some communities' customs for this day include feeding birds and reciting the Song of the Sea out loud in the regular prayer service.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] In traditional Sabbath Torah reading, the parashah is divided into seven readings, or עליות‎, *aliyot*.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] In the Masoretic Text of the Tanakh (Hebrew Bible), Parashat Beshalach has eight "open portion" (פתוחה‎, *petuchah*) divisions (roughly equivalent to paragraphs, often abbreviated with the Hebrew letter פ‎ (*peh*)).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] Parashat Beshalach has four further subdivisions, called "closed portion" (סתומה‎, *setumah*) divisions (abbreviated with the Hebrew letter ס‎ (*samekh*)) within the open portion divisions.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The first open portion divides the first reading.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The second open portion covers the balance of the first and all of the second readings.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The third open portion is coincident with the third reading.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The fourth open portion covers the fourth and fifth readings.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The fifth open portion is coincident with the sixth reading.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The sixth and seventh open portion divisions divide the seventh reading.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] And the eighth open portion is coincident with the *maftir* (מפטיר‎) reading that concludes the parashah.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] Closed portion divisions separate the fourth and fifth readings and divide the fifth and sixth readings.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] In the first reading, when Pharaoh let the Israelites go, God led the people roundabout by way of the Sea of Reeds.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] Moses took the bones of Joseph with them.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] God went before them in a pillar of cloud by day and in a pillar of fire by night.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The first open portion ends here with the end of chapter 13.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] In the continuation of the reading in chapter 14, God told Moses to tell the Israelites to turn back and encamp by the sea, so that Pharaoh might think that the Israelites were trapped and follow after them.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] When Pharaoh learned that the people had fled, he had a change of heart, and he chased the Israelites with chariots.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] In the short second reading, Pharaoh overtook the Israelites by the sea.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] Greatly frightened, the Israelites cried out to God and complained to Moses.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] Moses told the people not to fear, for God would fight for them.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The second reading and second open portion end here.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] In the third reading, God told Moses to lift up his rod, hold out his arm, and split the sea.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] Moses did so, and God drove back the sea with a strong east wind, and the Israelites marched through on dry ground, the waters forming walls on their right and left.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The Egyptians pursued, but God slowed them by locking their chariot wheels.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The third reading and the third open portion end here.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] In the long fourth reading, on God's instruction, Moses held out his arm, and the waters covered the chariots, the horsemen, and all the Egyptians.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] Moses and the Israelites—and then Miriam—sang a song to God, celebrating how God hurled horse and driver into the sea.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The fourth reading and a closed portion end here.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] In the short fifth reading, the Israelites went three days into the wilderness and found no water.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] When they came to Marah, they could not drink the bitter water, so they grumbled against Moses.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] God showed Moses a piece of wood to throw into the water, and the water became sweet.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] God told Moses that if he would diligently hearken to God and obey God's commandments, then God would give the Israelites none of the diseases that God had given the Egyptians.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] In the continuation of the reading, the Israelites traveled to the springs and palms of Elim, and then came to the wilderness of Sin and grumbled in hunger against Moses and Aaron.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] In the continuation of the reading, God told Moses that God would rain bread from heaven, and twice as much on the sixth day.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] Moses and Aaron told the Israelites that they would see God's glory, for God had heard their murmurings against God, and the Israelites saw God's glory appear in a cloud.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The fifth reading and the fourth open portion end here.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] In the sixth reading, God heard their grumbling, and in the evening quail covered the camp, and in the morning fine flaky manna covered the ground like frost.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The Israelites gathered as much of it as they required; those who gathered much had no excess, and those who gathered little had no deficiency.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] Moses instructed none to leave any of it over until morning, but some did, and it became infested with maggots and stank.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] On the sixth day they gathered double the food, Moses instructed them to put aside the excess until morning, and it did not turn foul the next day, the Sabbath.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] Moses told them that on the Sabbath, they would not find any manna on the plain, yet some went out to gather and found nothing.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] In the continuation of the reading, Moses ordered that a jar of the manna be kept throughout the ages.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The sixth reading and the fifth open portion end here with the end of chapter 16.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] In the seventh reading, in chapter 17, when the Israelites encamped at Rephidim, there was no water and the people quarreled with Moses, asking why Moses brought them there just to die of thirst.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] God told Moses to strike the rock at Horeb to produce water, and they called the place Massah (trial) and Meribah (quarrel).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] In the continuation of the reading, Amalek attacked Israel at Rephidim.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] Moses stationed himself on the top of the hill, with the rod of God in his hand, and whenever Moses held up his hand, Israel prevailed; but whenever he let down his hand, Amalek prevailed.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] When Moses grew weary, he sat on a stone, while Aaron and Hur supported his hands, and Joshua overwhelmed Amalek in battle.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] In the *maftir* reading that concludes the parashah, God instructed Moses to inscribe a document as a reminder that God would utterly blot out the memory of Amalek.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The seventh reading, the eighth open portion, and the parashah end here.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] Commentators note that the Hebrew Bible repeats the commandment to observe the Sabbath 12 times.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] Genesis 2:1–3 reports that on the seventh day of creation, God finished God's work, rested, and blessed and hallowed the seventh day.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The Sabbath is one of the Ten Commandments.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] Exodus 20:8–11 commands that one remember the Sabbath day, keep it holy, and not do any manner of work or cause anyone under one's control to work, for in six days God made heaven and earth and rested on the seventh day, blessed the Sabbath, and hallowed it.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] In the incident of the manna in Exodus 16:22–30, Moses told the Israelites that the Sabbath is a solemn rest day; prior to the Sabbath one should cook what one would cook and lay up food for the Sabbath.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] And God told Moses to let no one go out of one's place on the seventh day.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] In Exodus 35:1–3, just before issuing the instructions for the Tabernacle, Moses again told the Israelites that no one should work on the Sabbath, specifying that one must not kindle fire on the Sabbath.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] In Leviticus 23:1–3, God told Moses to repeat the Sabbath commandment to the people, calling the Sabbath a holy convocation.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The prophet Isaiah taught in Isaiah 1:12–13 that iniquity is inconsistent with the Sabbath.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] In Isaiah 58:13–14, the prophet taught that if people turn away from pursuing or speaking of business on the Sabbath and call the Sabbath a delight, then God will make them ride upon the high places of the earth and will feed them with the heritage of Jacob.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] And in Isaiah 66:23, the prophet taught that in times to come, from one Sabbath to another, all people will come to worship God.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The prophet Jeremiah taught in Jeremiah 17:19–27 that the fate of Jerusalem depended on whether the people abstained from work on the Sabbath, refraining from carrying burdens outside their houses and through the city gates.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] The prophet Ezekiel told in Ezekiel 20:10–22 how God gave the Israelites God's Sabbaths, to be a sign between God and them, but the Israelites rebelled against God by profaning the Sabbaths, provoking God to pour out God's fury upon them, but God stayed God's hand.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] 1 Maccabees 2:27–38 told how in the 2nd century BCE, many followers of the pious Jewish priest Mattathias rebelled against the Seleucid king Antiochus IV Epiphanes.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] Antiochus's soldiers attacked a group of them on the Sabbath, and when the Pietists failed to defend themselves to honor the Sabbath (commanded in, among other places, Exodus 16:22–30), a thousand died.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] 1 Maccabees 2:39–41 reported that when Mattathias and his friends heard, they reasoned that if they did not fight on the Sabbath, they would soon be destroyed.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p01] So they decided that they would fight against anyone who attacked them on the Sabbath.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The Mekhilta of Rabbi Ishmael interpreted the words "God led them not by the way of the land of the Philistines, although that was near" in Exodus 13:17 to indicate that God recognized that the way would have been nearer for the Israelites to return to Egypt.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] A midrash compared the words of Exodus 13:17, "God led the people about," to a merchant who bought a cow for use in his home and not for slaughter.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] As the merchant's house was near the slaughterhouse, he thought to himself that he had better lead the new cow home by another route, for if he led the cow past the slaughterhouse and it saw the blood there, it might turn tail and flee.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The Rabbis taught in a baraita that on the days of the 8-day Passover holiday, Jews read the various passages in the Torah relating to Passover.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Thus, on the seventh day of Passover, Jews read Exodus 13:17–15:26 and as haftarah 2 Samuel 22:1–51.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] A midrash employed a fanciful translation of Exodus 13:18 to imagine God's response to the Israelites' complaints in the wilderness.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The midrash taught that God asked the Israelites whether when a mortal king went into the wilderness, the king found there the same ease, the same food, or the same drink that he enjoyed in his own palace.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The midrash taught that the Israelites, however, were slaves in Egypt, and God brought them out of there and caused them to recline on lordly couches.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] In support of this, the midrash reread Exodus 13:18, "But God led the people about, (וַיַּסֵּב‎, *vayaseiv*) by the way of the wilderness," reading וַיַּסֵּב‎, *vayaseiv*, to mean God caused them "to recline" (using the same root סבב‎, *svv*) in the manner of kings reclining upon their couches.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The Mekhilta of Rabbi Ishmael interpreted the word translated as "armed" (חֲמֻשִׁים‎, *chamushim*) in Exodus 13:18 to mean that only one out of five (חֲמִשָּׁה‎, *chamishah*) of the Israelites in Egypt left Egypt; and some say that only one out of 50 did; and others say that only one out of 500 did.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The Jerusalem Talmud explained the same word to imply that the people departed Egypt with some 15 types of weaponry at their disposal.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The Mishnah cited Exodus 13:19 for the proposition that Providence treats a person measure for measure as that person treats others.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] And so because, as Genesis 50:7–9 relates, Joseph had the merit to bury his father Jacob and none of his brothers were greater than he was, so Joseph merited the greatest of Jews, Moses, to attend to his bones, as reported in Exodus 13:19.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] And Moses, in turn, was so great that none but God attended him, as Deuteronomy 34:6 reports that God buried Moses.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Similarly, the Tosefta cited Exodus 13:19 for the proposition that as Joseph had the merit of burying Jacob, so it was that only Moses took the trouble to care for Joseph's bones.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The Tosefta deduced from this that the rest of the Israelites were occupied with plunder, but Moses occupied himself with performing a commandment.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] When the Israelites saw Moses caring for Joseph's bones, they concluded that they should let Moses do so, so that Joseph's honor would be greater when his rites were taken care of by great people instead of unimportant people.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Citing Exodus 13:19, the Tosefta taught that just as "Moses took the bones of Joseph with him" into the Levites' camp, so one who was impure by reason of corpse contamination—and even a corpse—could enter the Temple Mount.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] A midrash illustrated a precept to finish what one starts by citing how Moses began performing a commandment by taking the bones of Joseph with him, as Exodus 13:19 reports, but failed to complete the task.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Thus Rabbi Hiyya bar Abba taught that if one begins a precept and does not complete it, the result will be that he will bury his wife and children.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The midrash cited as support for this proposition the experience of Judah, who began a precept and did not complete it.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] When Joseph came to his brothers and they sought to kill him, as Joseph's brothers said in Genesis 37:20, "Come now therefore, and let us slay him," Judah did not let them, saying in Genesis 37:26, "What profit is it if we slay our brother?" and they listened to him, for he was their leader.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] And had Judah called for Joseph's brothers to restore Joseph to their father, they would have listened to him then, as well.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] So when the brothers sold Joseph, it was from Shechem that they sold him, as Genesis 37:13 reports, "And Israel said to Joseph: 'Do not your brothers feed the flock in Shechem?'" God told the brothers that since they had sold Joseph from Shechem, they needed to return Joseph's bones to Shechem.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Rabbi Jose the Galilean taught that the "certain men who were unclean by the dead body of a man, so that they could not keep the Passover on that day" in Numbers 9:6 were those who bore Joseph's coffin, as implied in Genesis 50:25 and Exodus 13:19.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The Gemara cited their doing so to support the law that one who is engaged on one religious duty is free from any other.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The Tosefta also taught that God gave the Israelites seven clouds in the wilderness—one on their right, one on their left, one before them, one, behind them, one over their heads, and one among them.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The Gemara told that Rav Joseph's wife used to kindle the Sabbath lights late (just before nightfall).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Rav Joseph told her that it was taught in a baraita that the words of Exodus 13:22, "the pillar of cloud by day, and the pillar of fire by night, departed not," teach that the pillar of cloud overlapped the pillar of fire, and the pillar of fire overlapped the pillar of cloud.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] So she thought of lighting the Sabbath lights very early.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] But an elder told her that one may kindle when one chooses, provided that one does not light too early (as it would not evidently honor the Sabbath) or too late (later than just before nightfall).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] A midrash taught that a slave's master wept when slaves escaped, while the slaves sang when they had thrown off bondage.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] So the Egyptians wept when the Israelites escaped (as Exodus 14:5 reports).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The Israelites, however, chanted a song when they were released from bondage.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Reading Exodus 14:6, "And he made ready his chariot," to indicate that Pharaoh prepared his chariot personally, a midrash remarked that surely, he had plenty of slaves who could have done so for him.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The midrash concluded that the intensity of Pharaoh's hate thus upset the natural order.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] A baraita in the Jerusalem Talmud noted that Exodus 14:6, "With three on all of them," reported chariots with three horses, while Genesis 41:43, "And he made him ride in his double chariot," reported chariots with two horses.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The baraita deduced that at first, though the time of Joseph, only two horses pulled chariots, but a later Pharaoh made chariots drawn by three horses.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] And the baraita further reported that the Roman Empire made chariots drawn by four horses.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Rabban Gamaliel said that the Egyptians pursued after the Israelites as far as the Reed Sea and encamped behind them.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The enemy was behind them, and the sea was in front of them.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The Israelites saw the Egyptians and became greatly afraid.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The Israelites cast away all their Egyptian abominations, repented sincerely, and called upon God, as Exodus 14:10 reports, "And when Pharaoh drew near, the children of Israel lifted up their eyes." Moses saw the Israelites' anguish and prayed on their behalf.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] In a baraita, Rabbi Judah taught that the Israelites tried God with ten trials: two at the sea, two with water, two with the manna, two with the quail, one with the Golden Calf, and one in the wilderness of Paran.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The Gemara explained that of the two at the sea, one was in Exodus 14:11, when the Israelites said, "Because there were no graves in Egypt, have you taken us away to die in the wilderness?
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The Jerusalem Talmud noted that in Exodus 14:13–14, Moses made four responses to the complaining Israelites: "(1) Fear not, stand still, and see the salvation of the Lord, which God will work for you today; (2) for the Egyptians you have seen today, you shall never see them again.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] (3) The Lord will fight for you, and (4) you be quiet." The Jerusalem Talmud taught that at the sea, the Israelites divided into four groups.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Rabbi Meir taught that when the Israelites stood by the sea, the tribes competed over who would go into the sea first.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Then Naḥshon ben Aminadab stepped forward and went into the sea first, praying in the words of Psalm 69:2–16, "Save me O God, for the waters come into my soul.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] I sink in deep mire, where there is no standing . . . .
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Similarly, a midrash taught that Naḥshon was called that name because he was the first to plunge into the wave (נַחשׁוֹל‎, *naḥshol*) of the sea.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] And Rabbi Simeon bar Yochai said that God told Moses that because Naḥshon sanctified God's Name by the sea, he would get to be the first to present his offering in the newly constructed Tabernacle, as reported in Numbers 7:12.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Similarly, Rabbi Akiva said that the Israelites advanced to enter the Reed Sea, but they turned backwards, fearing that the waters would come over them.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The tribe of Judah sanctified God's Name and entered the sea first, as Psalm 114:2 says, "Judah became his sanctuary (in order to sanctify God), Israel his dominion." The Egyptians wanted to follow the Israelites, but they turned back, fearing that the waters would return over them.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] God appeared before them like a man riding on the back of a mare, as it is said in Song of Songs 1:9, "To a steed in Pharaoh's chariots." Pharaoh's horse saw the mare of God, and it neighed and ran into the sea after it.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Reading Exodus 14:15, "And the Lord said to Moses: 'Why do you cry to Me?
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Speak to the children of Israel, that they go forward," Rabbi Eliezer taught that God was telling Moses that there is a time to pray briefly and a time to pray at length.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] God was telling Moses that God's children were in trouble, the sea cut them off, the enemy pursued, and yet Moses stood and said a long prayer!
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] God told Moses that it was time to cut short his prayer and act.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Rabbi (Judah the Prince) taught that in Exodus 14:15, God was saying that the Israelites' faith in God was sufficient cause for God to divide the sea for them.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] For notwithstanding their fear, the Israelites had believed in God and followed Moses that far.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Rabbi Eliezer said that on the third day of creation, when God said in Genesis 1:9, "Let the waters be gathered together," the waters of the Reed Sea congealed and were made into twelve valleys (or paths), corresponding to the twelve tribes of Israel.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] And they were made into walls of water between each path, and between each path were windows.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Rabbi Joḥanan taught that God does not rejoice in the downfall of the wicked.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] But God rebuked them: "The work of my hands is being drowned in the sea, and you want to sing songs?" Rabbi Eleazar replied that a close reading of Deuteronomy 28:63 shows that God does not rejoice personally but does make others rejoice.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Rabbi Eliezer said that a maidservant at the sea saw what Isaiah and Ezekiel and the prophets never saw.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The Pirke De-Rabbi Eliezer recounted that Moses cried out to God that the enemy was behind them and the sea in front of them, and asked which way they should go.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] So God sent the angel Michael, who became a wall of fire between the Israelites and the Egyptians.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The Egyptians wanted to follow the Israelites, but they are unable to come near because of the fire.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The school of Rabbi Ishmael reasoned from the meaning of the word "in the midst" (בְּתוֹךְ‎, *be-tokh*) in Exodus 14:22 to resolve an apparent contradiction between two Biblical verses.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Rabbi Zerika asked about an apparent contradiction of Scriptural passages in the presence of Rabbi Eleazar, or, according to another version, he asked in the name of Rabbi Eleazar.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Exodus 24:18 says: "And Moses entered into the midst of the cloud," whereas Exodus 40:35 reads: "And Moses was not able to enter into the tent of meeting because the cloud abode thereon." The Gemara concluded that this teaches us that God took hold of Moses and brought him into the cloud.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Rabbi Hama ben Hanina deduced from Exodus 1:10 that Pharaoh meant: "Come, let us outwit the Savior of Israel." Pharaoh concluded that the Egyptians should afflict the Israelites with water, because as indicated by Isaiah 54:9, God had sworn not to bring another flood to punish the world.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The Egyptians failed to note that while God had sworn not to bring another flood on the whole world, God could still bring a flood on only one people.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] Rabbi Simon said that on the fourth day, the Israelites encamped by the edge of the sea.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The Egyptians were floating like skin-bottles upon the surface of the waters, and a north wind cast them opposite the Israelites' camp.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p02] The Israelites saw the Egyptians and recognized them, saying that these were officials of Pharaoh's palace, and those were taskmasters.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Rabbis in the Talmud gave differing explanations of how, as Exodus 15:1 reports, the Israelites sang the song of Exodus 15:1–19 along with Moses.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Rabbi Akiva taught that Moses sang the entire song, and the Israelites respond after him with the leading word, as where an adult read the Hallel (Psalms 113–118) for a congregation and they responded after him with the leading word (or some say, with "Hallelujah").
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Gemara explained that each of the three interpreted Exodus 15:1: Rabbi Akiva held that the word "saying" in Exodus 15:1 refers to the first clause, "I will sing to the Lord," and that was the Israelites' only response.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Rabbi Eliezer son of Rabbi Jose the Galilean held that "saying" refers to every clause of the song.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] And Rabbi Nehemiah held that "and spoke" indicates that they all sang together, and "saying" indicates that Moses began first.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Rabbi Meir taught in a baraita that Exodus 15:1 provides a proof of the resurrection of the dead in the Torah.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Exodus 15:1 says: "Then Moses and the children of Israel *will* sing this song to the Lord." It does not say "sang" but "will sing," indicating that Moses will come back to life and sing the song in the future.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Rabbi Eliezer taught that the words of Exodus 15:2, "*This* is my God, and I will glorify Him," indicate that the lowliest servant-girl at the Red Sea perceived what the prophets Isaiah and Ezekiel had not, for she saw God.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] A baraita taught that the words of Exodus 15:2, "This is my God, and I will adorn him," teach that one should adorn oneself before God in the fulfillment of the commandments.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Thus, the Gemara taught that in God's honor, one should make a beautiful sukkah, a beautiful lulav, a beautiful shofar, beautiful tzitzit, and a beautiful Torah Scroll, and write it with fine ink, a fine reed pen, and a skilled penman, and wrap it about with beautiful silks.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Abba Saul interpreted the word for "and I will glorify Him" (וְאַנְוֵהוּ‎, *v'anveihu*) in Exodus 15:2 to mean "and I will be like Him." Thus, Abba Saul reasoned, we should seek to be like God.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Just as God is gracious and compassionate, so should we be gracious and compassionate.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Reading the words of Exodus 15:2, "This is my God and I will praise Him, *my father's God* and I will exalt Him," Rabbi Jose the Galilean taught that even newborn and suckling children all saw God's Presence (*Shechinah*) and praised God.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Rabbi Meir said that even fetuses in their mothers' wombs sang the song, as Psalm 68:27 says, "Bless the Lord in the Congregations, even the Lord, from the source of Israel." (And a person's "source" is the womb.) The Gemara asked how fetuses could see the Divine Presence.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Rabbi Tanḥum said that the abdomen of pregnant women became transparent, and the fetuses saw.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Tosefta deduced from Exodus 1:22 that the Egyptians took pride before God only on account of the water of the Nile, and thus God exacted punishment from them only by water when in Exodus 15:4 God cast Pharaoh's chariots and army into the Reed Sea.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Abba Hanan interpreted the words of Psalm 89:9, "Who is a mighty one like You, O God?" to teach: Who is like God, mighty in self-restraint, that God heard the blaspheming and insults of the wicked Titus and kept silent?
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] A midrash taught that as God created the four cardinal directions, so also did God set about God's throne four angels—Michael, Gabriel, Uriel, and Raphael—with Michael at God's right.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The midrash taught that Michael got his name (*Mi-ka'el*, מִי-כָּאֵל‎) as a reward for the way that he praised God in two expressions that Moses employed.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Reading Exodus 15:11, the Pirke De-Rabbi Eliezer taught that the Israelites said to God that there is none like God among the ministering angels, and therefore all the angels' names contain part of a Name for God (אֱלֹהִים‎, *Elohim*).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] For example, the names Michael and Gabriel contain the word אֱל‎, *El*.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Pirke De-Rabbi Eliezer noted that Exodus 15:11 does not employ the words "fearful in *praise*," but "fearful in *praises*." For the ministering angels sing praises on high, and Israel sings praises on earth below.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Rabbi Judah ben Simon expounded on God's words in Deuteronomy 32:20, "I will hide My face from them." Rabbi Judah ben Simon compared Israel to a king's son who went into the marketplace and struck people but was not struck in return (because of his being the king's son).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] But the father asked the son whether he thought that he was respected on his own account, when the son was respected only on account of the respect that was due to the father.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] So the father renounced the son, and as a result, no one took any notice of him.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] So when Israel went out of Egypt, the fear of them fell upon all the nations, as Exodus 15:14–16 reported, "The peoples have heard, they tremble; pangs have taken hold on the inhabitants of Philistia.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Then were the chiefs of Edom frightened; the mighty men of Moab, trembling takes hold upon them; all the inhabitants of Canaan are melted away.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Terror and dread falls upon them." But when Israel transgressed and sinned, God asked Israel whether it thought that it was respected on its own account, when it was respected only on account of the respect that was due to God.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] So God concluded to chastise and try them with suffering.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] And the words, "till Your people pass over, O Lord," in Exodus 15:16 allude to the first advance of the Israelites into the Promised Land in the days of Joshua.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] And the words, "till the people pass over whom You have gotten," in Exodus 15:16 allude to the second advance of the Israelites into the Promised Land in the days of Ezra.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The baraita thus concluded that the Israelites were worthy that God should perform a miracle on their behalf during the second advance as in the first advance, but that did not happen because the Israelites' sin caused God to withhold the miracle.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Gemara counted Exodus 15:18, "The Lord shall reign for ever and ever," among only three verses in the Torah that indisputably refer to God's Kingship, and thus are suitable for recitation on Rosh Hashanah.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Gemara cited the language of Exodus 15:18, "The Lord shall reign for ever and ever," as a premier example of how Scripture indicates permanence.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] A baraita taught at the school of Rabbi Eliezer ben Jacob said that wherever Scripture employs the expression נֶצַח‎, *nezach*; סֶלָה‎, *selah*; or וָעֶד‎, *va'ed*; the process to which it refers never ceases.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Sages taught in a baraita in the Babylonian Talmud that seven prophetesses prophesied on behalf of the Jewish people.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Gemara identified them as Sarah, Miriam, Deborah, Hannah, Abigail, Huldah, and Esther.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Gemara explained that Miriam was a prophetess, as Exodus 15:20 says: "And Miriam the prophetess, the sister of Aaron, took a timbrel in her hand." The Gemara asked why this verse mentions only Aaron and not Moses.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Rav Naḥman said that Rav said that she prophesied when she was only Aaron's sister, before Moses was born, saying that her mother was destined to bear a son who would deliver the Jewish people to salvation.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] When Moses was born, the entire house was filled with light, and her father stood and kissed her on the head and told her that her prophecy had been fulfilled.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] But when Moses was cast into the river, her father patted her on the head, asking what had become of her prophecy, as it looked as though Moses would soon die.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] That is why Exodus 2:4 reports: "And his sister stood at a distance to know what would be done to him," for Miriam wanted to know how her prophecy would be fulfilled.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Similarly, the Mekhilta of Rabbi Ishmael, reading the words, "And Miriam the Prophetess," in Exodus 15:20, asked where Miriam had prophesied.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Mekhilta reported that Miriam had told her father that he was destined to have a son who would save Israel from the hands of the Egyptians.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Then, after the events of Exodus 2:1–3, Miriam's father reproached her, asking what had become of her prediction.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Gemara deduced from Exodus 15:26 that Torah study keeps away painful sufferings.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] It is gone." And רֶשֶׁף‎, *reshef*, refers only to painful sufferings, as Deuteronomy 32:24 says, "The wasting of hunger, and the devouring of the fiery bolt (רֶשֶׁף‎, *reshef*).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Rabbi Joḥanan said to Rabbi Simeon ben Lakish that even school children know that the Torah protects against painful disease.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Tosefta taught that those who superstitiously whisper over a wound and say the words of Exodus 15:26, "all of the diseases . . . ," and spit over the wound have no share in the world to come.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Gemara concluded that the manna fell in different forms for different classes of people: For the righteous, it fell as bread; for average folk, it fell as cakes that required baking; and for the wicked, it fell as kernels that required grinding.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Mishnah taught that the manna that Exodus 16:14–15 reports came down to the Israelites was among 10 miraculous things that God created on Sabbath eve at twilight on the first Friday at the completion of the creation of the world.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Rabbi Simeon ben Gamliel deduced from Exodus 16:14 that dew has been cursed.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] For in earlier times, when dew descended on straw and stubble, it whitened it, as Exodus 16:14 says, "And behold, on the face of the wilderness, was something thin, flaky, fine as frost upon the land." But now, dew blackens straw and stubble.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] A midrash read the words "but some of them left of it until the morning" in Exodus 16:20 to refer to the people who lacked faith.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Rabbi Simeon ben Lakish identified them with Dathan and Abiram, reasoning that Numbers 16:26 uses the word "men" to refer to Dathan and Abiram, and thus the word "men" in Exodus 16:20 must also refer to them.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Reading the words "and it bred worms and rotted" in Exodus 16:20, a midrash asked whether anything exists that first produces worms and then rots (implying that surely, rot precedes worms).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Answering in the negative, the midrash taught that God wished to reveal to people the deeds of those who disobeyed and saved the manna, so God caused many worms to breed during that night so that the sinners should not be able to smell the staleness of the manna in the evening and throw it out.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The midrash told that Moses became so angry with them that he forgot to tell them to gather two omers for each person on the sixth day.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] For this reason, the midrash taught, in Exodus 16:28, God asked, "How long will you refuse to keep My commandments and My laws?" including Moses among them (as Moses should not have given vent to his anger, thereby forgetting God's command).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Tractate Shabbat in the Mishnah, Tosefta, Jerusalem Talmud, and Babylonian Talmud interpreted the laws of the Sabbath in Exodus 16:23 and 29; 20:8–11; 23:12; 31:13–17; 35:2–3; Leviticus 19:3; 23:3; Numbers 15:32–36; and Deuteronomy 5:12.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Reading the words "*See* that the Lord has given you the Sabbath" in Exodus 16:29, a midrash asked why it says "see" when "know" would have been better.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Alphabet of Rabbi Akiva taught that when God was giving Israel the Torah, God told them that if they accepted the Torah and observed God's commandments, then God would give them for eternity a most precious thing that God possessed—the World To Come.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] When Israel asked to see in this world an example of the World To Come, God replied that the Sabbath is an example of the World To Come.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Tractate Eruvin in the Mishnah, Tosefta, Jerusalem Talmud, and Babylonian Talmud interpreted the laws of not walking beyond permitted limits in Exodus 16:29.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Avot of Rabbi Natan read the listing of places in Deuteronomy 1:1 to allude to how God tested the Israelites with ten trials in the Wilderness, and they failed them all, including at Exodus 17:3.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Avot of Rabbi Natan interpreted the words "On the plain" in Deuteronomy 1:1 to allude to how they complained about not having water, as Exodus 17:3 reports.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] In the Mekhilta of Rabbi Ishmael, Rabbi Eliezer said that the Israelites at Massah said that if God satisfied their needs, they would serve God, but if not, they would not serve God.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Mishnah reported that in synagogues at Purim, Jews read Exodus 17:8–16.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Mishnah quoted Exodus 17:11, which described how when Moses held up his hand, Israel prevailed and asked whether Moses' hands really made war or stopped it.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Rather, the Mishnah read the verse to teach that as long as the Israelites looked upward and submitted their hearts to God, they would grow stronger, but when they did not, they would fall.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Mishnah taught that the fiery serpent placed on a pole in Numbers 21:8 worked much the same way, by directing the Israelites to look upward to God.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The offender would thus be prevented from doing repentance and would not have the power to return from the offense, and the offender would die and be lost because of the offense.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Maimonides made clear that God did not decree that Pharaoh harm the Jewish people; rather, Pharaoh sinned willfully on his own, and he thus deserved to have the privilege of repentance withheld from him.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Baḥya ibn Paquda cited Exodus 15:26 for the proposition that the relation of nature to the Torah is that of a servant to a master, and the forces of nature operate in harmony with the teaching of the Torah.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Reading the account of Massah and Meribah in Exodus 17:1–7, Isaac Abravanel argued that if the Israelites lacked drinking water, then they were justified in complaining, and to whom should they have turned if not to their leader Moses?
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] So Abravanel asked why Exodus 17:7 should term this conduct of theirs "trying," as it appeared to be an absolutely legitimate and essential request.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Everett Fox noted that "glory" (כְּבוֹד‎, *kevod*) and "stubbornness" (כָּבֵד לֵב‎, *kaved lev*) are leading words throughout the book of Exodus that give it a sense of unity.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] But later, to their astonishment, the seas rose high without any wind.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Fitch said that God permits the wicked to accomplish some of their evil purposes against the just, but in the end frustrates them.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The 19th century pre-Civil War African-American spiritual "Mary Don't You Weep" employed the image of Moses at the shore of the sea and the liberation of the Israelites in the context of slavery in the United States.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Its propositions are presented to the understanding, submitted for consideration, without being forced upon our belief.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Belief and doubt, assent and opposition, in Mendelssohn's view, are not determined by desire, wishes, longings, fear, or hope, but by knowledge of truth and untruth.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Hence, Mendelssohn concluded, ancient Judaism has no articles of faith.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] James Kugel wrote that scholars have established that Semitic languages did not originally have a definite article (corresponding to the word "the" in English), but later developed one (the prefix הַ‎, *ha*, in Hebrew).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Oden grouped Exodus 15 along with Judges 5, Habakkuk 3, and Psalm 68 as exemplars of holy war hymns that revealed the religion of the Tribal League that preceded the formation of Israel.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Similarly, Propp considered it likely that the Song of the Sea (Exodus 15:1b–18HE) originally circulated independently and should thus be considered another source.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] : The introduction announces the core theme.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] : The second core element, a triumphal procession of the Victor to the throne.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] In Exodus 15:11, "Who is like you among the gods, O Lord?" John J.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Collins found continuity with the Mesopotamian view of divinity that freely granted the reality of other gods.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] In 1950, the Committee on Jewish Law and Standards of Conservative Judaism ruled: "Refraining from the use of a motor vehicle is an important aid in the maintenance of the Sabbath spirit of repose.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Such restraint aids, moreover, in keeping the members of the family together on the Sabbath.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Baruch Spinoza taught that religion only acquires the force of law by means of a sovereign power.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Therefore, Moses was not able to punish those who, before the covenant, and consequently while still in possession of their rights, violated the Sabbath (in Exodus 16:27).
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] However, Moses was able to do so after the covenant (in Numbers 15:36), because all the Israelites had then yielded up their natural rights, and the ordinance of the Sabbath had received the force of law.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Nehama Leibowitz argued that the sin with which the Israelites were charged at Massah was that of trying to find out whether belief in God was worthwhile.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Leibowitz said that the Israelites did not really need to ask if God was among them or not, for surely they had by then plainly benefitted from God's kindnesses on more than one occasion.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The concluding blessing of the *Shema*, immediately prior to the *Amidah* prayer in each of the three prayer services recounts events from Exodus 14:21–31.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Passover Haggadah, in the *magid* section of the Seder, recounts the reasoning of Rabbi Jose the Galilean that as the phrase "the finger of God" in Exodus 8:15 referred to 10 plagues, "the great hand" (translated "the great work") in Exodus 14:31 must refer to 50 plagues upon the Egyptians.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The references to God's mighty hand and arm in Exodus 15:6, 12, and 16 are reflected in Psalm 98:1, which is also one of the six Psalms recited at the beginning of the Kabbalat Shabbat prayer service.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] And the statement of God's eternal sovereignty in Exodus 15:18 also appears verbatim in the *Kedushah D'Sidra* section of the *Minchah* service for Shabbat.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The people's murmuring at Massah and Meribah, and perhaps the rock that yielded water, of Exodus 17:2–7 are reflected in Psalm 95, which is in turn the first of the six Psalms recited at the beginning of the Kabbalat Shabbat prayer service.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] In the Weekly Maqam, Sephardi Jews each week base the songs of the services on the content of that week's parashah.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] For Parashat Beshalach, Sephardi Jews apply Maqam Ajam, which commemorates the joy and song of the Israelites as they crossed the sea.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] For Ashkenazi Jews, the haftarah is the longest of the year.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The haftarah for Beshalach tells the story of Deborah.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] At 52 verses, it is the longest haftarah.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Both the parashah and the haftarah contain songs that celebrate the victory of God's people, the parashah in the "Song of the Sea" about God's deliverance of the Israelites from Pharaoh, and the haftarah in the "Song of Deborah" about the Israelites' victory over the Canaanite general Sisera.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Both the parashah and the haftarah report how the leaders of Israel's enemies assembled hundreds of chariots.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Both the parashah and the haftarah report how God "threw . . . into panic" (*va-yaham*) Israel's enemies.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Both the parashah and the haftarah report waters sweeping away Israel's enemies.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Both the parashah and the haftarah report singing by women to celebrate, the parashah by Miriam, and the haftarah by Deborah.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] Finally, both the parashah and the haftarah mention Amalek.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Gemara tied together God's actions in the parashah and the haftarah.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] To reassure the Israelites that their enemies did not still live, God had the Reed Sea spit out the dead Egyptians.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] To repay the seas, God committed the Kishon River to deliver one-and-a-half times as many bodies.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] To pay the debt, when Sisera came to attack the Israelites, God had the Kishon wash the Canaanites away.
[src:ark-of-bulrushes/beshalach-p03] The Gemara calculated one-and-a-half times as many bodies from the numbers of chariots reported in Exodus 14:7 and Judges 4:13.
